Learn how Git works internally with simple diagrams

Praveen Muthukumarana
Feb 22, 2019 · 9 min read

1: Different states of a file
2: Four areas of git
3: Create a new git repository
4: Create a new file
5: Stage the file
6: Commit the file
7: Create a new branch
8: Understand how stash work

We use git commands like git add index.js, git commit -m “message” daily without really knowing what they mean. Most of the time our code is synced without any issue. But sometimes things go wrong; we commit the wrong changes, or we end up having merge conflicts. In these scenarios, it would be helpful to have a solid understanding of how Git works in order to fix them.

Different states of a file ( According to git)

untracked — You create a brand new file called names.txt in your project. The file is now in untracked state.

staged — You execute command git add names.txt . Now the file is staged.

committed — You execute commit -m "names file added" . Now the change is committed. Here, the “change” is the creation of the new file.

modified — You add the text hello world to the file and save the file. Now the file is modified.

When you execute git add names.txt the file will be staged and the cycle continues.

The four areas of git

Git stores your data in four main areas.

  • Working Directory
  • Index (also known as Staging area)
  • Repository
  • Stash

Working directory — When a file is untracked or modified, its changes are stored in the working directory.

Index — When a file is staged, its changes are stored in the index.

Repository — When changes in a file are committed its stored in the repository.

We will learn what stash does later in the article.

Now, let us see how the rest of the 3 areas works in real life.

Initialize a new git repository

Create a new folder on the computer. Assume that this folder is our project we want to source control with git.

Issue this command from the root of this folder to initialize a new git repository.

git init

We will ignore the stash section for now.

At the current moment, this is the state of the remaining three areas.

There are no files in our project yet. Therefore all the areas are empty.

We are in the branch Master which is created by default when we initialized git.

Create a new file

We create a new text file named names.txt.

We add this text to the file and save it.

John
James
Mary

If you recall the keywords we learned earlier, now the file is inuntracked state.

Type this command to see the status of your git repository.

git status

Git will notify that there is an untracked file.

Notice that the file name is given in red. This signifies that the file has unstaged changes.

The new file and its changes are in the working directory.

Stage the file

Let us stage the file.

git add names.txt

This command stages the changes in names.txt. Now the file is added to the index area.

If you execute git status again, the file names.txt is shown in green. This signifies that the changes in the file have been staged.

Commit the file

git commit -m "names file created"

This command creates the first commit of our repository.

What is a commit?

A commit records the changes that were staged when the commit was made. In this case, the changes that this commit recorded are

  • Creation of the filenames.txt .
  • Adding the three names John, James and Mary to the file.

It also stores a reference to its parent commit. Since this is the first commit, it doesn’t have a parent.

You can view the git log to see a list of all commits.

git log

As seen here we only have a single commit yet.

b5cdeb1... is known as the commit hash. Each commit in a repository is given a unique commit hash.

Now, the changes are stored in the repository as a commit.

Here, the changes recorded by the current commit is marked in red. The whole file is red because this commit marks the creation of this file. Also, the text in the file is also red because it was added during the same commit.

Master

Master is the branch which was created by default when we initialized a new repository. A branch is simply a pointer that points at a particular commit. By default, the branch will always point at the latest commit made in it.

HEAD

HEAD is also a pointer that points to a particular commit. By default HEAD is attached to the current branch pointer. In this case, it points at Master. We will learn about HEAD later in the tutorial.

Modify the content of names.txt

John
James
Raj

We replace the name Mary with Raj.

Since the file is modified it is reflected in the Working Directory.

If you execute git status , the file names.txt is in red colour. This means it has unstaged changes.

Let us stage them.

git add names.txt

This will add the changes to the index.

And finally, we commit.

git commit -m "mary replaced by raj"

This is our git log.

Our visual diagram now looks like this.

In our second commit, only Raj is in red. This is because that’s the only change that was done to the file in that commit. Git tracks lines in your file. Not words.

So, this is how this change is recorded in Git.

Third line of names.txt changed from Mary to Raj.

Remember that by default, the branch will point at it’s latest commit. Therefore, Master moved from commitbefcdeb1to the new commitc35e2dd . Since the HEAD is attached at to Master, it too was moved with it.

Now the parent of the latest commit c35e2dd is b5cdeb1. This is shown by the blue arrow.

If you are still confused I’ll lay down the changes recorded by each commit.

b5cdeb1 — New file names.txt was created. This text was added to it.

John
James
Mary

c35e2dd — The text in line 3 was changed to Raj.

John 
James 
Raj

Move to the different commit with git checkout

We saw that HEAD is attached to Master and moves with it. With the git checkout command, we can move the HEAD to any commit in the repository we want.

When the HEAD moves to a different commit, both the index and the working directory is updated to reflect the state of the files up to that commit.

git checkout b5cdeb1

This command will move the head to the previous commit.

This is the output you will get.

HEAD is now in detached state. That means it is not attached to any branch.

Let us visualize this.

First, the HEAD moves to commitb5cdeb1.

Next, both the index and the working directory are updated to the state of the repository by that particular commit.

Now, if you open names.txt it will say Mary instead of Raj.

Let us attach the HEAD back to the Master branch.

git checkout Master

Recall that a branch is also just a pointer at a specific commit.

So bothgit checkout Master and git checkout ef56264 will point the HEAD to the same commit. But with the latter command, the HEAD is still detached. In git checkout Master you attach the HEAD to the branch pointer so that it moves with it when new commits are added to the branch.

Again both the Working Directory and the Index will be modified to the state of the repository at the commit the HEAD is pointed at.

Create a new branch

git checkout -b fullNames

Earlier with the checkout command, we moved the HEAD to a specific commit. We learned that since branches are references to specific commits, giving a branch name with checkout moves the HEAD to the latest commit of that branch.

But in this case, there is no branch called fullNames. That is why we use -b flag It says, create a new branch and checkout to it.

This is how it will look.

Even though we did a checkout to a new branch fullName, that is still pointing at the commit c35e2dd.

Let us now add surnames to all the names and make a commit.

names.txt is changed to.

John Grisham
James Fonterra
Raj Singh

Stage the changes.

git add names.txt

Commit.

git commit -m "Added surnames to names"

Now, the branch fullName is pointing at 76de724; The latest commit made in it. The HEAD also moved with it.

Understand how stash work

Remember we said that there are 4 areas in Git. So far we only talked about working directory, index and the repository. The third is the stash. Now let us see how this works.

checkout back to Master.

git checkout Master

Next, modify the name.txt to give it a title.

Employee List
John
James
Raj

Stage the changes.

git add names.txt

You remember that there is some urgent work to be done at the branch fullName and you have to checkout to that.

As we saw earlier when we checkout to a branch, both the index and the working directory are updated to the state of its latest commit. We would lose all the uncommitted changes in Master. We don’t want to commit unfinished work either.

In our example, it is only a single line and hardly matters. But in a scenario where you made a lot of changes, you don’t want to lose them.

The stash is a place where you can temporarily save uncommitted files both in the working directory and the index.

This is done with this command.

git stash

Now the changes are removed from the working directory and the index and stored in the stash.

We checkout to fullName. There, we make some changes and commit them.

ba36596 is the new commit made in fullName.

After work in firstName is complete, we checkout back to Master.

Now we want to put the stashed changes back to the working directory and the index.

git stash pop

This command will remove the items from the stash and apply to the index and working directory.

Ending note

I hope this article will help you become more productive using Git. Next time you type out a git command, try to visualize how data is moved between the 4 areas of Git. Cheers!
